Abdul Qadeer Khan, the father of Pakistan's nuclear program, supplied weapons-grade uranium to Iran and Libya, accelerating their nuclear ambitions.
Despite reports of collaboration with the US, Pakistan denies aiding in targeting Iranian weapons sites.
Khan's illicit activities have raised concerns about nuclear proliferation.
The US refrained from direct access to Khan, fearing revelations of military involvement.
The International Atomic Energy Agency continues to investigate Iran's nuclear program.
Khan's actions, driven by ideology and greed, have significantly impacted global security.
Pakistan asserts its capability to manage nuclear proliferation independently, rejecting US involvement in the matter.
